x4freetext: Deuteron energy was 23.2 MeV.
Solid-state nuclear track detector (SSNTD)
packets, consisting of electroplated fission deposits
(samples) plus mica track detectors for fission
fragment counting, were placed at 41 mm from the beam
spot in the Be target at approx. 0 Degree.
The mica SSNTD detectors were etched and the
fission tracks were counted after irradiation to
determine the fission ratios. A cadmium shield behind
the irradiated stack was used to eliminate low-energy
neutrons back scattered by the room walls.
Mass assay was based on 2*Pi alpha counting for
uranium deposits and counting of Pa-233 produced by
thermal neutrons in Th-232 for thorium deposits.
The neutron spectrum was determined with the unfolding
code SAND-II using a set of 11 measured activities,
the mean neutron energy for 0.3 - 23 MeV being 7.5 MeV
( from M.A.Lone et al, Nucl. Instr. Meth., 143, 331-
Fissions per atom were determined taking into account
deposits mass and isotopic composition.
Corrections have been made for fission fragment
absorption in the deposits, for beam current
fluctuations, for small flux differences due to
position in the stack  and to different foil diameter,
and for alpha backscattering in the foil backing.
The main two elements to be considered in the
error estimation are mass assay and fission-track
counting.
The error in mass assay is determined by the
uncertainties in (%):
U-235 alpha decay half life               .07
U-236 alpha decay half life               .06
U-238 alpha decay half life               .05
correction for alpha backscattering
in the foil backing    0.1
thorium weight                            0.1
alpha desintegration ratio for natural uranium:
alpha counting and corrections for alpha self-
absorption ( values not given explicitely in paper).
the error in fission track counting is determined by:
error in counting statistics ( no explicite value
given in original paper) and
systematic errors arising from fission rates
corrections, which are:
position in stack                 2 - 5
stack to source distance                 1.0
fission fragment range in uraniumoxide   10.
fission fragment range in thoriumoxide   30.
correction for fissions from other isotopes,
which depends on uncertainties in:
isotopic composition ( see under `sample`
in subents 003 - 008)
(calculated)integral fission cross section  5.
Data are taken from Table 5 of INDC(ARG)-010.
